#: ../../firewall.rst:250
msgid "Traffic shaping"
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:252
msgid ""
":index:`Traffic shaping` allows to apply priority rules on network traffic "
"through the firewall. In this way it is possible to optimize the "
"transmission, check the latency and tune the available bandwidth."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:256
msgid ""
"To enable traffic shaping it is necessary to know the amount of available "
"bandwidth in both directions and fill in the fields indicating the speed of "
"the Internet link. Be aware that in case of congestion by the provider there"
" is nothing to do in order to improve performance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:260
msgid ""
"Traffic shaping can be configured from the page :menuselection:`Traffic "
"shaping` -> :guilabel:`Interface rules`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:262
msgid ""
"The system provides three levels of priority, high, medium and low: as "
"default all traffic has medium priority. It is possible to assign high or "
"low priority to certain services based on the port used (eg low traffic peer"
" to peer)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:265
msgid ""
"The system works even without specifying  services to high or low priority, "
"because, by default, the interactive traffic is automatically run at high "
"priority (which means, for example, it is not necessary to specify ports for"
" VoIP traffic or SSH). Even the traffic type PING is guaranteed high "
"priority."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:271
msgid ""
"Be sure to specify an accurate estimate of the bandwidth on network "
"interfaces."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:275
msgid "Firewall objects"
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:277
msgid ""
":index:`Firewall objects` are representations of network components and are "
"useful to simplify the creation of rules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:280
msgid ""
"There are 6 types of objects, 5 of them represent sources and destinations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:282
msgid ""
"Host: representing local and remote computers. Example: web_server, pc_boss"
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:283
msgid ""
"Groups of hosts: representing homogeneous groups of computers. Hosts in a "
"host group should always be reachable using the same interface. Example: "
"servers, pc_segreteria"
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:285
msgid ""
"CIDR Networks: You can express a CIDR network in order to simplify firewall "
"rules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:287
msgid ""
"Example 1 : last 14 IP address of the network are assigned to servers "
"(192.168.0.240/28)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:289
msgid ""
"Example 2 : you have multiple green interfaces but you want to create "
"firewall rules only for one green (192.168.2.0/24)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:293
msgid ""
"*Zone*: representing networks of hosts, they must be expressed in CIDR "
"notation. Their usage is for defining a part of a network with different "
"firewall rules from those of the nominal interface. They are used for very "
"specific needs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:295
msgid ""
"By default, all hosts belonging to a zone are not allowed to do any type of "
"traffic. It's necessary to create all the rules on the firewall in order to "
"obtain the desired behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:297
msgid "The last type of object is used to specify the type of traffic:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:299
msgid ""
"Services: a service listening on a host with at least one port and protocol."
" Example: ssh, https"
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:301
msgid ""
"When creating rules, you can use the records defined in :ref:`dns-section` "
"and :ref:`dhcp-section` like host objects. In addition, each network "
"interface with an associated role is automatically listed among the "
"available zones."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:306
msgid "IP/MAC binding"
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:308
msgid ""
"When the system is acting as DHCP server, the firewall can use the list of "
"DHCP reservations to strictly check all traffic generated from hosts inside "
"local networks. When :index:`IP/MAC binding` is enabled, the administrator "
"will choose what policy will be applied to hosts without a DHCP reservation."
" The common use is to allow traffic only from known hosts and block all "
"other traffic. In this case, hosts without a reservation will not be able to"
" access the firewall nor the external network."
msgstr ""

